transcript: ‚Äâ In the upper echelons of fashion, luxury isn't simply a fad; it's a way of life. Style, substance and sentiment converge in a finished product that reflects as much on the skill of its creation as on the individual wearing it. In the realm of women's luxury shoes, Versace embodies this notion with fearless design principles, a rich artistic heritage and an inimitable sense of elegance. Women's Luxury Shoes and the Language of Fashion Some say that a woman's shoes are the cornerstone of her style, in both the literal and figurative sense. In the world of luxury fashion, they tell a story all their own, one of social standing, personal agency and unique expression. Whether it's a beautifully designed high heel or an unforgettable boot design, a shoe can strike up a conversation by doing nothing more than simply existing. These aren't items that foster a certain style; they are the style. Aesthetic Meets Artistry The hallmark of luxurious shoes is a powerful blend of visual allure and labour-intensive artistry. Each pair in the collection of women's luxury shoes from Versace is a testament to just that. Sculptural heels, sumptuous textures, the label's signature motifs and a bold exploration of colour abound with every style, and nothing is an afterthought. Superlative materials, including luxe leather and supple suede, paired with polished metal accents, are married to the techniques of practised artisans, ensuring that these shoes deliver comfort in addition to longevity. And more importantly? They're built to be every bit as useful as they are beautiful. Versatility Rooted in Bold Design Perhaps one of the most exciting aspects of the collection of Versace women's luxury shoes is that they're so far from single-use. That says nothing for everything we've seen them prove themselves in the unrelatable environment where they made their first appearance on the runways. Designed for the Modern Woman The luxury consumer of today has evolved. She requires more than beautiful shoes; she needs authenticity, she needs a story, and she needs purpose. The luxury consumer of today is the elegant woman of today. She expects her shoes to be an extension of the strong, sophisticated and stylish way she lives her life. These shoes aren't possessions to behold; they are statements to be expressed in. Each heel, each boot, each sandal is a visual dialogue on her life and the story she wants to tell. Investing in Timeless Luxury Luxury isn't the style of today; it is the construction, design and quality that will last for years to come. Versace women's luxury shoes are the embodiment of this ethos, luxury footwear that stands the test of time. Behind each pair of shoes, there is a story of unparalleled quality. Creating a luxury shoe is a craft: from the first sketch to the last stitch, it requires a sense of beauty that makes the pursuit more than just worth doing. Versace women's luxury shoes are more than just a trend: they are an homage to grace, strength and individual style. In a world where first impressions carry immense weight, they make sure that every step tells her story and sings her song, a sound and style that can't be mistaken for any other. Share this‚Ä¶

transcript: ‚Äâ Well, as you should know, a large fraction--but not majority--of people here purchase luxury handbags associated with Houses that have been in the industry for a *long* time. Your brand, unfortunately, won't reach a cult following any time soon; it takes decades to build and maintain that. So I would recommend you *not* rely on logo hardware or monograms of any sort. Every brand has a "story". It's a marketing tactic. I recommend you come up with one, and it doesn't have to be 100% true. You are welcome to embellish. You'd be surprised what a story can do. Chanel was a dying brand until Karl Lagerfeld took over. He reinvented the lore for the dying house and made Coco Chanel seem like the pinnacle of upper class from rags to riches (while simultaneously hiding her Nazi connections). What he did for the brand is immeasurable. Anyway, yeah, a good story always helps. Pick out your niche. What differentiates you from "other" handbag brands? Every brand is known for *something* . I wouldn't recommend going for "all our pieces are unique and handcrafted by the finest artisans" or "made with the higest quality leathers" as that has been over done and means very little to those actually into handbags. You need to pick a group--like age range and social economic status--you wish to appeal to. Have a distinct House code/style. You want to stick out. Having themes in your collection or iconic prints will help people recognise your product from afar. Think Chanel's quilted pattern, Burberry's Nova Check print, Versace's embellishments and safety pins, etc. All these repeat features help create world building, as we call it in the fashion world. Also, social media. I can't stress that enough.

transcript: ‚Äâ Donatella bids farewell with archives, supermodels and classic codes that sum up three decades at the helm of Versace. Donatella Versace, designer, entrepreneur and symbol of the brand, bids farewell to her position by reuniting the key figures who defined the house's imaginary. Versace's Fall 2025 campaign is not just a collection; it is a statement of affection. The campaign features Claudia Schiffer, Kate Moss, Amber Valletta, Kristen McMenamy, Natasha Poly, Saskia de Brauw, Anok Yai, Liu Wen, Mica Arga√±araz, Mila Van Eeten and Jacqui Hooper. All of them, wrapped in metal, archive and silhouettes portrayed by Mert & Marcus. 'Every collection is a story, and this is the story of Versace,' said Donatella. There is no nostalgia. There is narrative. What you see in this campaign is an intimate farewell that is not meant to be tragic, but celebratory. And among the eternal codes of the house's clothes, the liquid metal and the impossible waists, the new Virtus bag appears, called to be the symbol of this new stage. All this comes after months of speculation, confirmed this year with the purchase of Versace by the Prada Group for 1.25 billion euros. And with it, the appointment of Dario Vitale as the new creative director. The changeover is now official. Even so, Donatella, far from leaving, will continue as Versace's global ambassador.

transcript: ‚Äâ Versace Fall Winter 2025, Courtesy of Versace Donatella Versace's final campaign for the House that bears her name has arrived. Break the rules,‚Äù she declares, an ethos that has defined her reign and now becomes its closing refrain. Photographed by Mert & Marcus , the campaign unites familiar faces and signature styles. Claudia Schiffer , Kate Moss , Kristen McMenamy , Amber Valletta , Natasha Poly , Saskia de Brauw , Liu Wen , Mica Arga√±araz , Anok Yai, Mila Van Eeten and Jacqui Hooper return in looks that straddle both the past and present. Archival pieces, like the label's metallic mesh, appear alongside newer designs, including the Virtus bag adorned with the V-emblem. The collection reaffirms Donatella's long-standing fascination with contrasts: strength and sensuality, armor and elegance, control and chaos. Versace Fall Winter 2025, Courtesy of Versace The visuals are saturated in gold, casting a literal glow on the designer's final statement. According to Donatella, this campaign was about more than fashion: ‚ÄúThe energy on this campaign was extraordinary. It was all about friendship, loyalty, and love.‚Äù Her parting words extend beyond the clothes, shaping the tone of a legacy rooted in bold femininity and fearless attitude. Over the years, Donatella championed unapologetic glamour while pushing boundaries for women in fashion. Each of her collections told a story, of power, seduction, rebellion, and this final campaign threads those stories together into one cohesive narrative. It becomes both a retrospective and a vision for the future, positioning the Versace woman not as a figure of the past, but as a timeless presence with unstoppable force. Versace Fall Winter 2025, Courtesy of Versace As Donatella steps down, Versace enters a new era under Dario Vitale , formerly of Miu Miu. While all eyes are now on what comes next, this final campaign stands as a culmination of one of fashion's most formidable creative tenures, an unapologetic farewell that reflects the House's past while daring it to evolve.
